b'For the New Year, RD Molly Tevis says \xe2\x80\x9dinclude fermented foods. They are crucial for supporting gut health.\xe2\x80\x9d Kombucha, kimchi, sauerkraut, miso and yogurt are all great options!'

b'RD Molly Tevis explains \xe2\x80\x9calmost half of the U.S. population consumes less than the required amount of magnesium (400mg per day).\xe2\x80\x9d She suggests working avocado, nuts, legumes, tofu, leafy greens and even dark chocolate into your diet for a healthier New Year. Try this Curried Egg Salad with avocado recipe!'
b'RD Molly Tevis says DRINK MORE WATER in the New Year! It \xe2\x80\x9chelps regulate body homeostasis and eliminates waste.\xe2\x80\x9d'

b'RD Molly Tevis suggests adding more variety\xe2\x80\x94including colors\xe2\x80\x94to your diet in the New Year. \xe2\x80\x9cEach new food offers different nutrients and keeps healthy eating interesting,\xe2\x80\x9d she says.'

b'RD Molly Tevis says \xe2\x80\x9cGet cooking! Get your hands dirty in the kitchen making your own meals. You will reconnect with your food, slow down with eating and generally make healthier choices.\xe2\x80\x9d How about this meal prep chicken recipe to start?'

b'We asked Registered Dietitian, Molly Tevis, for some New Year nutrition tips. Her first is \xe2\x80\x9cfill half your plate with vegetables. No matter which diet, the base to any healthy lifestyle is always more vegetables.\xe2\x80\x9d'
